rComments: Worst Professor, boring,  my test grades were border line, not failing, however, he didn't count my class participation, in class work, homework, my project and my attendance, I don't think I deserved an "F", no warning, no return e-mails, i would NOT recommend him

Like other users have said: he's oldschool, i.e. no powerpoint.  He's an elderly man, so he spokes quietly, calmly.  He's a bit monotone and very boring.  But I think he knows his stuff because he's been to the places in canada that he lectures about.

He's sometimes a hard marker, and he doesn't always find the best way to explain things, but he's still a great teacher. He tought me many things hat are helpful to me now. He also had this strange sense of humor, but I liked him.

Extremely hard marker but very clear and willing to explain things over. Uses old style teaching = no powerpoint slides/pictures but does mention page numbers for pictures/maps for the textbook during lecture.
Horrible teacher and individual to work with.

Read over your notes after his class. It reads like a story about the little country that could. He's that concise. This guy is hard, but if you pay attention to his advice, you'll do well. I agree with the oddly funny remark. He was very intentionally humorous. One of my favorite UofT teachers. He made me interested in Canadian History. Fancy that

One of the History Department's most knowledgeable profs. This guy maybe old school, but he knows his stuff and is oddly funny. If you like eating moose meat or canoeing down the St. Lawrence River, you'll enjoy taking his class.
